<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-475-477  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 475 477.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Vision Graphics andamp; Image Processing  Oct 1990 v52 n1p110(14).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Using feature probabilities to reduce the expected computationalcost of template matching. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Margalit, Avraham; Rosenfeld, Azriel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A basic problem in vision and image processing is matching atwo-dimensional template and parts of a given digital image.andP;  Itis very difficult to solve the general problem of translation,rotation, scaling, and gray value invariant matching.andP;  Usingprobabilistic information obtained from the image and the templatecan reduce the cost of the template matching process.andP;  The methodfinds features that are relatively common in the template but arerare in the image, then finds locations in the image where thesefeatures are, and then performs an exhaustive search for validmatches in the area of these locations.andP;  Both the image and thetemplate are accepted as input by the template matching algorithm.andO;Using the four and eight nearest neighbor feature maps cansignificantly reduce the computational cost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AlgorithmsCost ReductionTwo-Dimensional GraphicsImage ProcessingComputer VisionProbability.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Percent of neighborhoods checked versus number of features.andO;(chart)Maximum number of searches needed to locate a template. (table)A template. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>